<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870826-0033 </DOCNO><HL> Jailed Black Leader MeetsWith South African Officials</HL><DD> 08/26/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> AFRIC </IN><DATELINE> JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP)  </DATELINE><TEXT>    One of South Africa'smost prominent jailed black leaders has met with governmentofficials for talks that could lead to his release, hislawyer said.   The black leader, Goven Mbeki, a former national chairman of the outlawed African National Congress, has been imprisoned since his 1964 conviction on sabotage charges. Mr. Mbeki, who is 76 years old, was among eight ANC members, including Nelson Mandela, who received life sentences at the trial.    Early last week, government officials met with Mr. Mbeki and &quot;posed various questions that may have to do with his release,&quot; said his attorney, Priscilla Jana.    Ms. Jana declined to provide details of the talks. She did say that neither she nor Mr. Mbeki had received any official notification concerning a possible release. </TEXT></DOC>